<subSubSection id="C33072C53465E46B9BA4FEA8FE82FDA3" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B95214E3465E46B9BA4FEA8FE82FDA3" blockId="18.[151,1436,153,539]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">
<emphasis id="B95EFD5C3465E46B9BA4FEA8FEE0FEA7" bold="true" box="[199,308,261,287]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C2A5ACD3465E46B9A25FEA8FD8EFEA7" baseAuthorityName="Sakai" baseAuthorityYear="1970" box="[326,602,261,287]" class="Malacostraca" family="Callianassidae" genus="Scallasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinophthalma">
<emphasis id="B95EFD5C3465E46B9A25FEA8FD8EFEA7" box="[326,602,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Scallasis spinophthalma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described on the basis of six female specimens (including three ovigerous specimens) and four detached chelipeds. An ovigerous specimen (cl 
<quantity id="4CD28CAB3465E46B9F0CFE84FB13FEFB" box="[1135,1223,297,323]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.3" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" unit="mm" value="4.3">4.3 mm</quantity>
) was designated as 
<typeStatus id="54919FEC3465E46B9BF4FEE0FF2EFEDF" box="[151,250,333,359]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">holotype</typeStatus>
. The species is notable for the broad maxilliped 3 ischium-merus and the distal margin of the merus much more rounded than in any other congeneric species (
<bibRefCitation id="EFBB5CBF3465E46B99BEFEDCFC88FE33" author="Sakai, K." box="[733,860,369,395]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" pagination="37 - 47" refId="ref11830" refString="Sakai, K. (1970) A small collection of the thalassinideans from the waters around Tsushima Islands, Japan, including a new species of Callianassa (Crustacea, Anomura). Publications of the Seto Marine Biological Laboratory, 28 (1), 37 - 47. https: // doi. org / 10.5134 / 175621" type="journal article" year="1970">Sakai 1970</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 4a; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBB5CBF3465E46B98DCFEDCFB59FE33" author="Komai, T. &amp; Ohtsuka, S. &amp; Nakaguchi, K. &amp; Go, A." box="[959,1165,369,395]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" pagination="19 - 73" refId="ref11376" refString="Komai, T., Ohtsuka, S., Nakaguchi, K. &amp; Go, A. (2002) Decapod crustaceans collected from the southern part of the Sea of Japan in 2000 - 2001 using TRV Toyoshio-maru. Natural History Research, 7 (1), 19 - 73." type="journal article" year="2002">
Komai 
<emphasis id="B95EFD5C3465E46B9F71FEDFFB97FE33" box="[1042,1091,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">et al</emphasis>
. 2002
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 9F, G). The species possesses a bi-articulate male pleopod 1 and biramous pleopod 2, more developed than in other species. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBB5CBF3465E46B9E70FE38FF35FE6B" author="Komai, T. &amp; Ohtsuka, S. &amp; Nakaguchi, K. &amp; Go, A." pageId="18" pageNumber="419" pagination="19 - 73" refId="ref11376" refString="Komai, T., Ohtsuka, S., Nakaguchi, K. &amp; Go, A. (2002) Decapod crustaceans collected from the southern part of the Sea of Japan in 2000 - 2001 using TRV Toyoshio-maru. Natural History Research, 7 (1), 19 - 73." type="journal article" year="2002">
Komai 
<emphasis id="B95EFD5C3465E46B9E06FE3BFA41FE17" box="[1381,1429,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">et al</emphasis>
. (2002)
</bibRefCitation>
did not illustrate female chelipeds, here illustrated (
<figureCitation id="13113DCB3465E46B9846FE14FC7FFE6B" box="[805,939,441,467]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1605,1630]" captionTargetBox="[165,1424,347,1574]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,345,1580]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 10. Scallasis spinophthalmus (Sakai, 1970). Male (cl 3.3 mm), CBM-ZC 6166: A, telson, dorsal view (setae partially omitted); D, left uropod, dorsal view (marginal setae on rami omitted). Female (cl 3.5 mm), CBM-ZC 6170: B, left major cheliped, lateral view; C, right minor cheliped, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3765547" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3765547/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Fig. 10B, C</figureCitation>
); the telson and left uropod are re-illustrated (
<figureCitation id="13113DCB3465E46B9BFCFE70FEF2FE4F" box="[159,294,477,503]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1605,1630]" captionTargetBox="[165,1424,347,1574]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,345,1580]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 10. Scallasis spinophthalmus (Sakai, 1970). Male (cl 3.3 mm), CBM-ZC 6166: A, telson, dorsal view (setae partially omitted); D, left uropod, dorsal view (marginal setae on rami omitted). Female (cl 3.5 mm), CBM-ZC 6170: B, left major cheliped, lateral view; C, right minor cheliped, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3765547" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3765547/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Fig. 10A, D</figureCitation>
) to show armature (facial spiniform setae and a spine on the uropodal endopod anterior margin) which were overlooked.
</paragraph>
